text=(:if [ authgroup @tas || authgroup @admins || equal {$Author} '' ]:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=edit|Edit this page]] \\%0aStatus: {GradebookArticles.{$Name}$:Status} %0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!{$:Category}]]%0a%0a!Sign language slips%0a%0a:Author: kushaanm%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aSlips of the hand in sign language%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aWhen reading through Dr. Julie Hochgesang's twitter, I found a tweet where she commented on her slip of the hand, which is analogous to a spoken slip of the tongue. She combined the movement of one word with the handshape of another. %0a%0aIt is not uncommon when speaking, to delete or combine parts of a sentence (e.g. "unanimity" -> "unamity"), and this is due to the way the brain stores language parameters. These errors expose the idea that the brain stores spoken language parts by their constituent sounds and meaning. %0a%0aA similar effect can be seen in sign languages, where there is instead slipping in the gestures. This implies that not only are there similarities in morphology and syntax, but also in the neural processes for both types of language. Slips are observed not only in Dr. Hochgesang's case, where she mixed up the parts of the sign, but also by substituting in signs for words with similar meanings. Slips imply that the mental dictionary for sign languages groups words based on how the forms are created (e.g. handshape), as well as meaning.  %0a%0aInterestingly, although there is relation, these are not the same channels. Hand slips do not occur at the same time as mouth ones do, when in parallel. Instead, these happen independently of each other, even though there is large similarity in the mental processes that led to the slip. %0a%0aSources: %0ahttps://theconversation.com/why-do-people-have-slips-of-the-tongue-191383%0ahttps://sites.google.com/a/students.colgate.edu/insights-from-sign-language/home/production-errors%0ahttps://twitter.com/jahochcam/status/1592645656120012802%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:elseif [ equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:andrewid} '' || equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:section} '' ] :)%0a%0aYou must enter your andrew ID and section before submitting an expansion. %0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a%0a----%0a(:if equal {$Author} {$:Author}:)%0a!!Change article category%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#changearticlecategory:)%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a%0a(:Section: E:)%0a(:Category: SignLanguage:)%0a(:Title: Sign language slips:)
